---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Stories by The Layer — Izu Peninsula, Japan"
  description="The thinking and evolution behind The Layer. Inspirations, craftspeople, renovations, and the places that shaped the project."
>
  <div class="page-header container">
    <p class="page-header__label">Stories</p>
    <h1>Where it started.</h1>
    <p class="page-header__sub">
      In 2020 we bought a house in Ito. We didn't knock it down and rebuild — we restored it.
      That decision became a project, and that project became The Layer.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="origin container" aria-labelledby="origin-heading">
    <div class="origin__content">
      <h2 id="origin-heading">The Ito House</h2>

      <p>
        We bought the house in September of 2020. According to the documents and the real estate agent,
        we are the third owners since the house was built in 1968. The story we were told is that it was
        built by a wealthy company executive who worked in steel — built for his lover to live in, and
        he would come down on weekends to see her. Eventually he passed away and she moved out, leaving
        the house empty throughout most of the 1980s and 90s.
      </p>

      <p>
        The next owner — the person we bought it from — was an artist, wife of a JAL pilot who had passed away.
        She used it as a weekend house and loved the garden. She sold it because her children thought she was
        getting too old to spend weekends there alone. She told us she was happy that we weren't going to knock
        it down. Plenty of people had told her exactly that — and she hadn't sold it to them. She gave us a
        small discount because we made it clear that we loved it and were going to restore it.
      </p>

      <p>
        We don't know who the builder was, though there is a builder's seal on some of the posts.
        What is clear is that the house was built with exceptional craftsmanship — our contractor,
        who worked with a team of skilled craftspeople on the renovation, felt the same.
      </p>

      <p>
        We did full renovations on the kitchen, bath and dressing room, and the toilet room.
        We added earthquake retrofitting and additional insulation. Then we updated all of the surfaces —
        new plaster, tatami, fusuma paper — and added some of our own style.
      </p>

      <p>
        The fusuma paper came from <a href="http://www.tokyomatsuya.co.jp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Tokyo Matsuya</a>,
        a paper maker in continuous operation since 1690. They have hundreds of historic woodblocks,
        still in use or reconstructed from centuries-old originals. Our choice — dark paper with a
        gold bamboo print — was perhaps a little unusual. They told us they enjoyed seeing younger
        people using these materials in renovations.
      </p>

      <p>
        One area we find particularly special is the woodwork and design of the genkan — a bit of
        mid-century influence, but still deeply traditional. The house has been rated one of Japan's
        finest short-term rentals by Condé Nast. We share before-and-after stories on
        <a href="https://www.instagram.com/thelayer.hotels/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Instagram</a>,
        because people always ask about the spaces and the materials.
      </p>

      <p>
        This was the beginning. From one restored house in Ito, the project grew into a collection.
        Atami Garden followed. Then the Atami Hotel. Each with its own history, its own materials,
        its own reason for being restored rather than rebuilt.
      </p>

      <blockquote>
        <p>Rather than destroy, layer and make anew.</p>
        <footer lang="ja">壊すのではなく、新しい層を重ねて創る。</footer>
      </blockquote>
    </div>

    <aside class="origin__aside">
      <div class="origin__fact">
        <p class="origin__year">2020</p>
        <p>First property acquired — the Ito house, built 1968</p>
      </div>
      <div class="origin__fact">
        <p class="origin__year">2022</p>
        <p>Atami Garden restored and opened</p>
      </div>
      <div class="origin__fact">
        <p class="origin__year">2026</p>
        <p>Atami Hotel opening — The Layer's first hotel</p>
      </div>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section class="stories-more container" aria-labelledby="stories-more-heading">
    <h2 id="stories-more-heading">More stories</h2>
    <p class="stories-more__sub">
      We plan to document the craftspeople, collaborators, suppliers, and places that have shaped
      The Layer — renovation notes, material discoveries, and the things that make each property
      what it is. More soon.
    </p>

    <div class="stories-categories">
      <div class="stories-category">
        <h3>Craftspeople & collaborators</h3>
        <p>The people behind the materials, the woodwork, the plaster, and the sound systems.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="stories-category">
        <h3>Renovation notes</h3>
        <p>Before and after, season by season — how the properties were found and what changed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="stories-category">
        <h3>Places & inspiration</h3>
        <p>The cafés, buildings, coasts, and cultural spaces that continue to shape the project.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="stories-category">
        <h3>Music & listening</h3>
        <p>The records, the listening rooms, the spaces that sound like themselves.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .page-header {
    padding-block: 4rem 2rem;
    max-width: 720px;
  }
  .page-header__label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    opacity: 0.5;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .page-header h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 4vw, 2.75rem);
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .page-header__sub {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
    opacity: 0.7;
    max-width: 600px;
  }

  .origin {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr;
    gap: 5rem;
    align-items: start;
    padding-block: 3rem 5rem;
    border-top: 1px solid #e5e5e5;
  }

  .origin__content h2 {
    font-size: clamp(1.25rem, 3vw, 1.75rem);
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  .origin__content p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.9;
    opacity: 0.78;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    max-width: 640px;
  }
  .origin__content a {
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 3px;
  }

  .origin__content blockquote {
    border-left: 2px solid #000;
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
    margin-block: 3rem 1rem;
  }
  .origin__content blockquote p {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    font-style: italic;
    opacity: 0.85;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .origin__content blockquote footer {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    opacity: 0.5;
    font-weight: 300;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
  }

  .origin__aside {
    position: sticky;
    top: 80px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1.5rem;
  }
  .origin__fact {
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border: 1px solid #e5e5e5;
  }
  .origin__year {
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }
  .origin__fact p:last-child {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    opacity: 0.65;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .stories-more {
    padding-block: 3rem 5rem;
    border-top: 1px solid #e5e5e5;
  }
  .stories-more h2 {
    font-size: clamp(1.25rem, 3vw, 1.75rem);
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }
  .stories-more__sub {
    font-size: 0.975rem;
    opacity: 0.65;
    max-width: 560px;
    line-height: 1.75;
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .stories-categories {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(240px, 1fr));
    gap: 2rem;
  }
  .stories-category {
    padding: 1.75rem;
    border: 1px solid #e5e5e5;
  }
  .stories-category h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
  }
  .stories-category p {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .origin {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 3rem;
    }
    .origin__aside { position: static; }
  }
</style>
